      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Why V-Containing Words Require Special Strategy</h2>
      <p>V is the only consonant in Scrabble with no valid two-letter word. This means you can't use the quick-play fallback that tiles like X (AX, EX, OX), Z (ZA, ZO), or J (JO) enjoy. When the board gets crowded, V can become a liability if you haven't planned your play in advance. The key is to use V early in the game while open lanes still exist.</p>
      <p>The silver lining? V pairs beautifully with other mid-to-high value letters. VORTEX combines V with X for 16 points. VIVIFY uses double-V plus F and Y for 18 points. SAVVY and HEAVY leverage V with Y for 14 points each. Words like VIVID, REVIVE, VELVET, and EVOLVE all use double-V to push past 12 points base value. When you draw V, think about pairing it with premium companions rather than trying to dump it cheaply — there's no cheap V dump available anyway.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Strategy Tips</h2>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Play V early:</strong> No two-letter V word exists, so V becomes harder to place as the board fills. Use it in the first half of the game while open lanes remain.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Pair V with high-value tiles:</strong> VORTEX (V+X), VIVIFY (V+F+Y), SAVVY (V+V+Y) — combining V with other premium letters maximizes its scoring potential.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Double-V words are your friends:</strong> VIVID, REVIVE, EVOLVE, VELVET — using both V tiles in one word clears your rack efficiently while scoring well.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>V on premium squares matters more:</strong> Since V has no two-letter shortcut, you need to make each V play count. V on DLS = 8 points; V on TLS = 12 points from one tile.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Consider exchanging late-game V:</strong> If the board is locked and you can't find a V play, exchanging is sometimes correct. V is the hardest consonant to play in tight positions.</span></li>
      </ul>

